calcDivStats <- function(d_file, pair_label){
  
  return(read_csv(
      d_file, col_names=c("window", "pair.aln.len", "pair.diffs", "out.aln.len", "pair.out.diffs", "x.out", "y.out")) %>%
        mutate(window = gsub(".filter.fa", "", window)) %>%
        # Parse the window name
        
        mutate(dxy.pair = pair.diffs / pair.aln.len) %>%
        # Calculate dxy for the pair of species using the pair alignment length
        
        mutate(dxy.jc.pair = -(3/4) * (log(1 - ((4/3) * dxy.pair)))) %>%
        mutate(dxy.jc.pair = ifelse(dxy.jc.pair == Inf, NA, dxy.jc.pair)) %>%
        # Calculate dxy with the JC correction for the pair of species using the pair alignment length
        
        mutate(dxy.pair.out = pair.out.diffs / out.aln.len) %>%
        # Calculate dxy for the pair of species using the alignment length with the outgroup
        
        mutate(dxy.jc.pair.out = -(3/4) * (log(1 - ((4/3) * dxy.pair.out)))) %>%
        mutate(dxy.jc.pair.out = ifelse(dxy.jc.pair.out == Inf, NA, dxy.jc.pair.out)) %>%
        # Calculate dxy with the JC correction for the pair of species using the alignment length with the outgroup
        
        mutate(dxout = x.out / out.aln.len) %>%
        # Calculate dxy for x and the outgroup
        
        mutate(dxout.jc = -(3/4) * (log(1 - ((4/3) * dxout)))) %>%
        mutate(dxout.jc = ifelse(dxout.jc == Inf, NA, dxout.jc)) %>%
        # Calculate dxy with the JC correction for x and the outgroup
        
        mutate(dyout = y.out / out.aln.len) %>%
        # Calculate dxy for y and the outgroup
        
        mutate(dyout.jc = -(3/4) * (log(1 - ((4/3) * dyout)))) %>%
        mutate(dyout.jc = ifelse(dyout.jc == Inf, NA, dyout.jc)) %>%
        # Calculate dxy with the JC correction for y and the outgroup
        
        mutate(dxy.out = (dxout + dyout) / 2) %>%
        mutate(dxy.jc.out = (dxout.jc + dyout.jc) / 2) %>%
        # Average d for x and y compared to the outgroup
        
        mutate(rnd = dxy.pair.out / dxy.out) %>%
        mutate(rnd.jc = dxy.jc.pair.out / dxy.jc.out) %>%
        # Calculate RND from the dxy using the alignment with the outgroup
        
        mutate(label = pair_label) %>%
        # Add the species label
        
        filter(pair.aln.len >= 5000) %>%
        
        filter(dxy.pair <= 0.10)
        
        # mutate(a.pair = pair.diffs / aln.len) %>%
        # mutate(d.pair.jc = -(3/4) * (log(1 - ((4/3) * a.pair)))) %>%
        # mutate(d.pair.jc = ifelse(d.pair.jc == Inf, NA, d.pair.jc)) %>%
        # mutate(a.out.x = x.out / aln.len) %>%
        # mutate(d.out.x.jc = -(3/4) * (log(1 - ((4/3) * a.out.x)))) %>%
        # mutate(a.out.y = y.out / aln.len) %>%
        # mutate(d.out.y.jc = -(3/4) * (log(1 - ((4/3) * a.out.y)))) %>%
        # mutate(a.out = (a.out.x + a.out.y) / 2) %>%
        # mutate(d.out.jc = (d.out.x.jc + d.out.y.jc) / 2) %>%
        # #mutate(d.out.jc = ifelse(is.nan(d.out.jc), NA, d.out.jc)) %>%
        # mutate(rnd = a.pair / a.out) %>%
        # mutate(rnd.log = log10(rnd)) %>%
        # mutate(rnd.jc = d.pair.jc / d.out.jc) %>%
        # mutate(rnd.jc.log = log10(rnd.jc)) %>%
        # #mutate(rnd.jc.log = ifelse(is.nan(rnd.jc.log), NA, rnd.jc.log)) %>%
        # mutate(label = pair_label)
  )
  
}

getBreakpointWins <- function(df, inv_df, threshold=100000){
  near_start_windows = df %>% distance_inner_join(inv_df, by=c("start"="start"), max_dist=threshold)
  # Use the distance_inner_join function to find windows that are within the threshold of the start values
  
  near_end_windows = df %>% distance_inner_join(inv_df, by=c("end"="end"), max_dist=threshold)
  # Use the distance_inner_join function to find windows that are within the threshold of the end values
  
  near_windows = bind_rows(near_start_windows, near_end_windows)
  # Combine the results
  
  df$near.breakpoint <- df$start %in% near_windows$start.x & df$end %in% near_windows$end.x
  # Add a new column near.breakpoint that is TRUE if the window is near the positions in the second data frame and FALSE otherwise

  return(df)
}

genChromoPlot <- function(chrome_str, label, features=FALSE, cur_feature=FALSE, num_flank_windows=0, multi_row=TRUE){
# chrome_str:       the chromosome to be subset
# label:            a title, not currently used
# features:         a set of coordinates to be marked on the chromoplot
# cur_feature:      if a single feature is provided here, the chromoplot will be subset to show just that region
# num_flank_window: the number of windows surrounding a feature to subset; to be used with cur_feature, otherwise ignored
# multi_row:        whether or not to display the top three topologies in separate rows on the chromoplot
  
  if(!cur_feature==FALSE){
    flank = num_flank_windows * window_size * 1000
    chrdata = subset(all_windows_f, chr==chrome_str & start > cur_feature$start - flank & end < cur_feature$end + flank)
  }else{
    chrdata = subset(all_windows_f, chr==chrome_str)
  }
  # Subset the data by chromosome and feature (if provided)

  ##########
  
  chr_len = chrdata[chrdata$chr==chrome_str, ]$chr.len[1]
  # Get the chromosome length
  
  chrdata$col.cat = NA
  chrdata$ystart = NA
  chrdata$yend = NA
  # Initialize some empty columns in the data
  
  cur_col = "#ffffff"
  topo_counts$topo.color = as.character(topo_counts$topo.color)
  # Other setup
  
  for(i in 1:nrow(chrdata)) {
    cur_topo_num = chrdata[i,]$topo.num.overall
    # Get the topology number/id of the current window
    
    if(aln_stats[aln_stats$window == chrdata[i,]$window,]$total.seqs.filter != 5){
      cur_col = "#999999"
      chrdata[i,]$ystart = 0
      chrdata[i,]$yend = 4
    # If this window was filtered out in the alignment steps, set the color to grey and the y coords to span the chromoplot (0 to 4)
    }else if(is.na(cur_topo_num)){
      cur_col = "#999999"
      chrdata[i,]$ystart = 0
      chrdata[i,]$yend = 4
    # If this window was filtered out otherwise, set the color to grey and the y coords to span the chromoplot (0 to 4)
    }else{
      cur_col = topo_counts$topo.color[topo_counts$topo.num.overall==cur_topo_num]
    # If this window was not filtered, set the current color to be the one for the rank by frequency
    }
    
    chrdata[i,]$col.cat = cur_col
    # Set the color for this window based on above
    
  }
  ## Categorize the windows and get their colors

  ##########
  
  if(multi_row){
    chrdata$ystart[chrdata$topo.rank.overall==1] = 4
    chrdata$yend[chrdata$topo.rank.overall==1] = 3
    
    chrdata$ystart[chrdata$topo.rank.overall==2] = 3
    chrdata$yend[chrdata$topo.rank.overall==2] = 2
    
    chrdata$ystart[chrdata$topo.rank.overall==3] = 2
    chrdata$yend[chrdata$topo.rank.overall==3] = 1
    
    chrdata$ystart[chrdata$topo.rank.overall>3] = 1
    chrdata$yend[chrdata$topo.rank.overall>3] = 0
  # If the plot is multi-line, topologies of rank 1, 2, and 3 get their own rows
  }else{
    chrdata$ystart = 1
    chrdata$yend = 0
  # If the plot is not multi-line, all columns go from 0 to 1
  }
  ## Set the y coordinates for the chromoplot
  
  ##########
  
  cols_labs = levels(as.factor(chrdata$col.cat))
  names(cols_labs) = levels(as.factor(chrdata$col.cat))
  # Set up the colors
  
  cur_len = max(chrdata$end) - min(chrdata$start)
  chr_breaks = seq(min(chrdata$start), max(chrdata$end), by=cur_len/5)
  # Set up the x-axis breaks
  
  chromoplot = ggplot(chrdata, aes(x=start, y=ystart, color=col.cat, fill=col.cat))
  
  if(!features==FALSE){
    offset = 3
    feature_cols = corecol(numcol=nrow(features), offset=offset)
    chromoplot = chromoplot +
      geom_rect(data=features, inherit.aes=F, aes(ymin=-Inf, ymax=Inf, xmin=start, xmax=end), alpha=0.2, fill=feature_cols) 
  }
    
  chromoplot = chromoplot + 
    geom_rect(aes(ymin=ystart, ymax=yend, xmin=start, xmax=end)) +
    scale_color_manual(values=cols_labs) +
    scale_fill_manual(values=cols_labs) +
    scale_x_continuous(limits=c(min(chrdata$start), max(chrdata$end)), breaks=chr_breaks) +
    xlab("Position") +
    bartheme() +
    theme(legend.position="none",
          legend.key.width = unit(0.75,  unit = "cm"),
          legend.spacing.x = unit(0.25, 'cm'),
          legend.title = element_blank(),
          #legend.text=element_text(size=12),
          axis.text=element_text(size=8),
          axis.title=element_text(size=10),
          axis.line.y=element_line(color="white"),
          axis.ticks.y=element_line(color="white"),
          axis.text.y=element_text(color="white"),
          axis.title.y=element_text(angle=0),
          plot.margin = unit(c(0,0,0,0), "cm")
  )

  if(!features==FALSE){
    offset = 3
    for(i in 1:nrow(features)){
      chromoplot = chromoplot +
        geom_vline(xintercept=features[i,]$start, color=corecol(numcol=1, offset=offset), size=1) +
        geom_vline(xintercept=features[i,]$end, color=corecol(numcol=1, offset=offset), size=1)
      offset = offset + 1
    }
  }
  # If a set of features have been provided to be marked, draw vertical lines at their boundaries here
  
  if(multi_row){
    chromoplot = chromoplot + 
      scale_y_continuous(limits=c(0,4), breaks=0.5:3.5, labels=c("0.0", "3", "2", "1")) +
      ylab("Topology")
  }else{
    chromoplot = chromoplot + 
      scale_y_continuous(limits=c(0,1), breaks=0.5:1.5, labels=c("0.0", "")) +
      ylab("Topology")
  }
  # Set up the y-axis based on whether the plot is multi-line or not
  
  return(chromoplot)
  # Return the plot
}
genRFPlot <- function(df, yvar, chrome_str, label, ylab, type="point", ymax=FALSE, quantline=FALSE, groups=FALSE, features=FALSE, cur_feature=FALSE, num_flank_windows=0, num_roll_windows=1){
# chrome_str:       the chromosome to be subset
# label:            a title, not currently used
# features:         a set of coordinates to be marked on the chromoplot
# cur_feature:      if a single feature is provided here, the chromoplot will be subset to show just that region
# num_flank_window: the number of windows surrounding a feature to subset; to be used with cur_feature, otherwise ignored
  
  chrdata = df %>%
    filter(chr == chrome_str)
  
  if(!cur_feature==FALSE){
    flank = num_flank_windows * window_size * 1000
    chrdata = chrdata %>%
      filter(start > cur_feature$start - flank & end < cur_feature$end + flank)
  }
  # Subset the data by chromosome and feature (if provided)

  chrdata = chrdata %>%
    arrange(start)
  
  if(!groups==FALSE){
    chrdata = chrdata %>%
      group_by(!!groups)
  }
  
  if(type=="roll"){
    chrdata = chrdata %>%
    mutate(!!yvar := rollapply(!! rlang::sym(yvar), width=num_roll_windows, FUN=function(x) mean(x, na.rm=TRUE), partial=F, fill=NA, align="left"))
  }
  
  ##########
  
  #qts = quantile(chrdata$wrf.st, probs=c(.05,.95), na.rm=T)
  # Calculate some percentiles (not currently used)
  
  cols = rev(c(corecol(pal="wilke", numcol=4, offset=4)))
  # Set up the colors (not currently used)

  cur_len = max(chrdata$end) - min(chrdata$start)
  chr_breaks = seq(min(chrdata$start), max(chrdata$end), by=cur_len/5)
  # Set up the x-axis breaks
  
  if(!groups==FALSE){
    wrf_adj = ggplot(chrdata, aes_string(x="start", y=yvar, color=groups)) +
      scale_color_manual(values=corecol(pal="wilke", numcol=length(unique(chrdata[[groups]]))))
  }else{
    wrf_adj = ggplot(chrdata, aes_string(x="start", y=yvar))
  }
  
  if(!features==FALSE){
    offset = 3
    feature_cols = corecol(numcol=nrow(features), offset=offset)
    wrf_adj = wrf_adj +
      geom_rect(data=features, inherit.aes=F, aes(ymin=0, ymax=Inf, xmin=start, xmax=end), alpha=0.1, fill=feature_cols)
  }
  
  if(type=="point"){
    wrf_adj = wrf_adj +
      geom_point(size=1, alpha=0.1)
      #geom_smooth(se=F)
  }else if(type == "line"){
    wrf_adj = wrf_adj +
      geom_line()    
  }else if(type == "roll"){
    wrf_adj = wrf_adj +
      #geom_line(aes(y=rollapply(chrdata[[yvar]], width=num_roll_windows, FUN=function(x) mean(x, na.rm=TRUE), partial=F, fill=NA, align="left")))
      geom_line()
  }else if(type == "smooth"){
    wrf_adj = wrf_adj +
      geom_smooth(se=F)
  }
  

  if(!quantline==FALSE){
    wrf_adj = wrf_adj +
      geom_hline(yintercept=quantline, size=0.75, linetype="dashed", color="#f0e442")
  }
  
  if(!ymax==FALSE){
    if(ymax=="logy"){
      wrf_adj = wrf_adj +
        scale_y_log10()
    }else{
      wrf_adj = wrf_adj +
        scale_y_continuous(limits=c(0, ymax))
    }
  }

  wrf_adj = wrf_adj +
    scale_x_continuous(limits=c(min(chrdata$start), max(chrdata$end)), breaks=chr_breaks) +
    xlab(NULL) +
    ylab(ylab) +
    bartheme() +
    #theme_classic() +
    theme(axis.text=element_text(size=8),
          axis.title=element_text(size=10),
          #axis.line.x=element_blank(),
          axis.ticks.x=element_blank(),
          axis.title.x=element_blank(),
          axis.text.x=element_blank(),
          axis.title.y=element_text(angle=0),
          plot.margin = grid::unit(c(0,0,0,0), "cm"),
          axis.ticks.length.x = unit(2, "pt"),
          legend.position="bottom")
          #plot.background = element_rect(color = "deepskyblue3", linewidth = 3))
    
  if(!features==FALSE){
    offset = 3
    for(i in 1:nrow(features)){
      wrf_adj = wrf_adj +
        geom_vline(xintercept=features[i,]$start, color=corecol(numcol=1, offset=offset), size=1) +
        geom_vline(xintercept=features[i,]$end, color=corecol(numcol=1, offset=offset), size=1)
      offset = offset + 1
    }
  }
  # If a set of features have been provided to be marked, draw v lines at their boundaries here
  
  leg = get_legend(wrf_adj)
  
  wrf_adj = wrf_adj + 
    theme(legend.position = "none")
  
  return(list(wrf_adj, leg))
  # Return the plot
}

In the plots below, I show several statistics on 10kb windows along mm10 chromosome 17 and outline the boundaries of the inversions. I show:

  1. For two branches, the divergence of each pair of sequences, \(d\) (or \(d_{XY}\)):

\[ d_{XY} = \frac{n_d}{n} \]

where \(n_d\) is the number of sites where the nucleotides differ between the two sequences and \(n\) is the total number of aligned (non-gap) sites between the two sequences.

  1. Relative Node Depth (\(RND\)) for the specified pair of sequences. This statistic uses \(d\) between a pair of species, \(d_{XY}\), and compares it to the average \(d\) from each species to an outgroup, \(d_{out}\). \(d_{XY}\) is calculated as above, while \(d_{XO}\) and \(d_{YO}\) are calculated the same way, but between species \(X\) and the outgroup, \(O\), and species \(Y\) and \(O\). Then,

\[ d_{out} = \frac{d_{XO} +d_{YO}}{2} \]

and

\[ RND = \frac{d_{XY}}{d_{out}} \]

LOWER values of \(RND\) can be indicative of introgression. See Rosenzweig et al. 2016 for more info. Each line represents one comparisong between a pair of species.

  1. Weighted Robinson-Foulds (wRF) distance between each window tree and the SPECIES TREE. I gave a brief explanation of wRF here. In this case, the REFERENCE TREE is ALWAYS the SPECIES TREE and the QUERY TREE is the tree inferred from that 10kb window. Each dot represents the wRF for one 10kb window.

  2. The chromoplot visualizing topological differences in window trees. The colors are the same as here.

For each panel, vertical shaded regions represent the locations of the inversions.

1.1 Additional filtering

In addition to the alignment site filtering and sequence presence filtering done previously, here we also apply the following filters:

  1. Remove any alignments shorter than 7500bp after the aforementioned site filtering.
  2. For a given species pair, for \(d_{XY}\) and \(RND\), remove any alignments for which the number of aligned (non-gap) sites between them is less than 5000bp.
  3. For a given species pair, for \(d_{XY}\) and \(RND\), remove alignments for which \(d_{XY} > 0.10\)

7 Baseline comparisons to non-inversion windows

doStats <- function(df, yvar, ylabel, filter_flag = FALSE){
  groupvar = "inv.overlap"

  df = df %>%
    drop_na(!!sym(yvar)) %>%
    filter(is.finite(!!sym(yvar)))
  
  if(filter_flag){
    df = df %>% filter(!!sym(yvar) < 1)
  }
  # Get rid of the NAs and filter values higher than 1
  #browser()
  df_anova = aov(reformulate(groupvar, yvar), data=df)
  df_anova_res = residuals(df_anova)
  df_anova_res_sample = sample(df_anova_res, 5000, replace=T)
  df_anova_shapiro = shapiro.test(df_anova_res_sample)
  # Do the ANOVA and check the distribution of the residuals
  
  #qqnorm(d_anova_res)
  #qqline(d_anova_res)
  
  cat("\n\n<details><summary>&#9654; Click to reveal ", ylabel, " stats</summary>\n")
  
  anova_qqplot = ggqqplot(df_anova_res) +
    ggtitle(paste(pair, " - ", ylabel, " - QQ Plot of Residuals")) +
    xlab("Theoretical Quantiles") +
    ylab("Sample Quantiles") +
    annotate("text", x=2, y=2, label=paste("Shapiro p-value =", round(df_anova_shapiro$p.value, digits = 5)))
  print(anova_qqplot)
  # Plot a qqplot to visualize
  
  cat(paste("```Shapiro p-value (null: ANOVA residuals are normally distributed): ", round(df_anova_shapiro$p.value, digits = 5), "```\n"))
  
  df_levene = leveneTest(df[[yvar]], df[[groupvar]], center=mean)
  cat(paste("```Levene p-value (null: variances among the groups are the same): ", round(df_levene[1, "Pr(>F)"]), "```\n"))
  # Check if for homoscedasticity between pairs of distributions
  
  cat("```Since data are not normal or homosecdastic, we don't do ANOVA.```\n")
  
  ## Check if data are normal and have homoscedasticity for an ANOVA (they aren't)
  ##########
  
  df_kw = kruskal.test(reformulate(groupvar, yvar), data=df)
  cat(paste("```Kruskal p-value (null: groups are the same): ", round(df_kw$p.value, digits = 5), "```\n"))
  # Perform the Kruskal test as a non-parametric alternative to ANOVA
  # to determine if groups are the same (null)
  
  cat("\n</details>")
  
  # d_dunn = dunnTest(d.out.jc ~ inv.overlap, data=kruskal_data, method="bonferroni")
  # d_dunn_df = as.data.frame(d_dunn$res)
  # # Dunn test for pairwise differences
  
  ##########

  inv_groups = unique(df[[groupvar]])
  # Get the list of inversion groups
  
  pairwise_results = data.frame()
  # Initialize a data frame to store the results
  
  for (i in 1:(length(inv_groups) - 1)) {
    for (j in (i + 1):length(inv_groups)) {
      # Loop over each pair of groups
      
      if(inv_groups[i] == "Non-inversion" || inv_groups[j] == "Non-inversion") {
        group1_data <- df[[yvar]][df[[groupvar]] == inv_groups[i]]
        group2_data <- df[[yvar]][df[[groupvar]] == inv_groups[j]]
        # Subset the data for the two groups
        
        wilcox_result <- wilcox.test(group1_data, group2_data, conf.int = TRUE)
        # Perform the Wilcox test
  
        pairwise_results = rbind(pairwise_results, data.frame(
          Group1 = inv_groups[i],
          Group2 = inv_groups[j],
          MedianDifference = wilcox_result$estimate,
          ConfLow = wilcox_result$conf.int[1],
          ConfHigh = wilcox_result$conf.int[2],
          wilcox.p = wilcox_result$p.value
        ))
        # Store the results
      }
    }
  }
  
  #print(pairwise_results)
  # Print the results
  #browser()
  pairwise_results$sig = "N.S."
  pairwise_results$sig <- ifelse(pairwise_results$wilcox.p <= 0.05, "*", pairwise_results$sig)
  pairwise_results$sig <- ifelse(pairwise_results$wilcox.p <= 0.01, "**", pairwise_results$sig)
  pairwise_results$sig <- ifelse(pairwise_results$wilcox.p <= 0.001, "***", pairwise_results$sig)
  # Add a significance label column 
  
  pairwise_results$GroupComparison = with(pairwise_results, paste(Group1, Group2, sep = " - "))
  pairwise_results$GroupComparison = with(pairwise_results, reorder(GroupComparison, GroupComparison))
  # Reorder the results alphabetically
  
  #pairwise_results$GroupComparison = with(pairwise_results, reorder(interaction(Group1, Group2), MedianDifference))
  # Reorder the results by the estimator
  
  # Plot the median differences with confidence intervals, colored by significance level
  pairwise_p = ggplot(pairwise_results, aes(x=GroupComparison, y=MedianDifference, color=sig)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=ConfLow, ymax=ConfHigh), width=0.2) +
    geom_hline(yintercept=0, size=1, linetype=2) +
    scale_color_manual(values=sig_cols, limits=names(sig_cols), drop=FALSE) +
    # ggtitle(paste(pair, "- shifts in ", ylabel)) +
    #xlab("Group Comparison") +
    ylab(paste("Estimated Shift in ", ylabel)) +
    bartheme() +
    theme(panel.grid.major.x=element_line(color="#d3d3d3", size=0.5, linetype=1),
          panel.grid.major.y=element_line(color="#d3d3d3", size=0.5, linetype=1),
          # plot.title = element_text(size=14, margin=margin(b=20)),
          axis.text.x = element_text(angle=25, hjust=1, size=8),
          axis.title.x = element_text(size = 10),
          axis.text.y = element_text(size=8),
          axis.title.y = element_text(size = 10),
          plot.margin = margin(0, 0.1, 0, 0, "cm"),
          legend.position="bottom"
          )
          #axis.title.y=element_text(size=12),
          #plot.margin=margin(0.5,0.5,0,0.5, unit="cm"))    
    #coord_flip()
  
  return(pairwise_p)
}

8 Percentage of each inversion that overlaps with coding exons

library(rtracklayer)
library(GenomicRanges)

#####

inversions_bed = import(here("data", "inversions.bed"))
# Read the bed file with inversions

inversion_lens <- width(inversions_bed)
# Calculate the length of each inversion in the BED file

#####

mm10_17_gff = import(here("data", "Mus_musculus.GRCm38.99.chromosome.17.gff3"))
seqlevels(mm10_17_gff) = paste0("chr", seqlevels(mm10_17_gff))
# Read GFF and add chr prefix to feature ids

chromosome_feature = mm10_17_gff[mm10_17_gff$type == "chromosome",]
chromosome_length = width(chromosome_feature)
# Get the length of the chromosome

coding_exons = mm10_17_gff[mm10_17_gff$type == "CDS"]
# Get the coding exon features

#####

inv_overlapping_exons = findOverlaps(coding_exons, inversions_bed)
inv_overlapping_regions = pintersect(coding_exons[queryHits(inv_overlapping_exons)], inversions_bed[subjectHits(inv_overlapping_exons)])
# Get the overlaps between coding exons and inversions

overlapping_bases_per_inv = sapply(seq_along(inversions_bed), function(i) {
  sum(width(inv_overlapping_regions[subjectHits(inv_overlapping_exons) == i]))
})
# Count overlapping bases for each inversion

overlap_percentage_per_inv = (overlapping_bases_per_inv / inversion_lens) * 100
# Calculate the percentage of each inversions that is overlapped

#####


chromosome_obj = GRanges(seqnames = "chr17", ranges = IRanges(start = 1, end = chromosome_length))
# Define the entire chromosome as a GRanges object

non_inv_regions = setdiff(chromosome_obj, inversions_bed)
# Calculate the regions of the chromosome that are not within any of the inversions


non_inv_overlapping_exons <- findOverlaps(non_inv_regions, coding_exons)
# Find the overlaps between non-inversions and the coding exons

non_inv_overlapping_bases <- sum(width(pintersect(non_inv_regions[queryHits(non_inv_overlapping_exons)], coding_exons[subjectHits(non_inv_overlapping_exons)])))
# Calculate the total number of overlapping bases

non_inv_percentage <- (non_inv_overlapping_bases / chromosome_length) * 100
# Calculate the percentage of the chromosome not within any of the BED regions that is overlapped by a coding exon

#####

inversions_bed$overlap.percentage = overlap_percentage_per_inv
# Add the overlap percentages to the BED table

non_inv_row = GRanges(seqnames = "chr17", ranges = IRanges(start=1, end=chromosome_length, overlap.percentage=non_inv_percentage))
mcols(non_inv_row)$name <- "Non-inversions"
# Create a new GRanges object for the non-inversion percentage

inversions_bed = append(inversions_bed, non_inv_row)
# Append the new row to the inversions_bed object

inversions_bed$overlap.percentage = inversions_bed$overlap.percentage / 100
inversions_bed$non.overlap.percentage = 1 - inversions_bed$overlap.percentage
# Calculate the percent of each region not overlapped by CDS

#####

inversions_bed_df = as.data.frame(inversions_bed)
# Convert the GRanges object to a data frame

inversions_bed_df = inversions_bed_df %>% select(-width)
# Remove the width column

inversions_bed_df_melt = melt(inversions_bed_df, id.vars = c("seqnames", "start", "end", "strand", "name"), variable.name = "type", value.name = "percentage")
inversions_bed_df_melt$type = fct_rev(inversions_bed_df_melt$type)
# Reshape the data to a long format

perc_cds_p = ggplot(inversions_bed_df_melt, aes(x = name, y = percentage, fill = type)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1)) +
  scale_y_continuous(expand=c(0,0)) +
  xlab("") +
  ylab("Proportion of bases") +
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#d3d3d3","#db6d00"), labels=c("Does not overlap CDS", "Overlaps CDS")) +
  bartheme() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom") +
  guides(fill = guide_legend(reverse = TRUE)) +
  coord_flip()
print(perc_cds_p)

9 dxy test

▶ Raw dxy vs Jukes-Cantor corrected dxy 
dxy_df = data.frame(dxy.raw = seq(from = 0, to = 1, by = 0.001))
dxy_df = dxy_df %>% mutate(dxy.jc = -(3/4) * (log(1 - ((4/3) * dxy.raw))))

dxy_p = ggplot(dxy_df, aes(x=dxy.raw, y=dxy.jc)) +
  geom_point(alpha=0.5) +
  geom_vline(xintercept=0.75) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0) +
  bartheme()
print(dxy_p)
